column10: b"b' HTML5 Upload fails for multiple files on latest Safari for Windows'"

b'b" The current stable Safari for Windows has a bug that causes the upload of multiple files through the HTML5 runtime to fail.  Curiously upload through HTML5 still works if only a single file is selected. The problem seems to be related to the FileList object available through the input element.  When more than one file is selected the file sizes are set to 0
column11: the modification time is also set to 0.  The resulting upload through the FormData object will upload a zero length (i.e. empty) file. This bug does not seem to be a web-kit bug as the latest Chrome does not have the same problem. I\'ve logged an issue with Apple against Safari. I\'ve also created a basic test case that uses the same technique to upload files that plupload does using HTML5 on Safari.  The test case is available here: url  (By the way I have not coded the test case to work around [this webkit form bug]url  which you may run into the second time you select files using the test)"'

column10: b"b' Provide access to full XHR response headers onerror'"
b'b\' The YouTube API handles uploads in a strange way where upon posting a video
column11: a 302 response is returned. It appears this is treated as an XHR error and Plupload cancels a post request before completion. It would be helpful to be able to access the XHR headers in the Error function to pull out the "Location" header.\''

column10: b"b' Copying this from the plupload forum
column11: since this seems like the place to address issues. As a followup: I\\xe2\\x80\\x99m using v2 of the YouTube API
column12: since v3 is not yet frozen
column13: and following the browser-based uploading pattern described here:url  For this pattern
column14: YouTube claims the expected response is a 301 (Moved Permanently) upon successful upload of a video
column15: but in my experience the API actually issues 302 (Found).url  Most other successful YouTube API interactions result in 200 or 201
column16: just not uploading. I\\xe2\\x80\\x99m basing the interaction partially on source for the CORS example page:url  I post some XML to youtube to create a video object on their end with particular metadata. They return a single-use url to upload the file to
column17: along with a permission token. The token and URL setting works
column18: and plupload uploads the file to youtube successfully (it shows up on my youtube profile)
column19: but the response from youtube never gets through and the connection is aborted. The response following a successful upload should be the aforementioned 302
column20: with the ID of the new video as one of the get params of the Location header URL. I guess I\\xe2\\x80\\x99m not entirely aware if the browser even lets you intercept 301/302 responses and access the \\xe2\\x80\\x9cLocation\\xe2\\x80\\x9d header. Reading the w3 spec it sounds like the expected behavior is to transparently follow the redirect.url url  It\\xe2\\x80\\x99s possible there is a cross-site issue and that I\\xe2\\x80\\x99m not setting headers correctly
column21: but I don\\xe2\\x80\\x99t think that\\xe2\\x80\\x99s the problem. Examining the request-response cycle with the Chrome Inspector or Wireshark shows that it seems to work OK
column22: but is aborted by Plupload or possibly the browser. I\\xe2\\x80\\x99m looking to grab the destination url for the redirect either from the \\xe2\\x80\\x9cLocation\\xe2\\x80\\x9d header
